1 The Prompt

Use lubridate to make an argument about whether Taylor can make it from her concert in Tokyo, Japan, on Saturday, 2/10/2024, at 6:00pm (you can assume the concert lasts about 5 hours) to the Super Bowl in Las Vegas, Nevada, on Sunday, 2/11/2024, at 3:30pm.

Code 
knitr::include_graphics("swift_FP.png")

2 Getting set up

First, youâll want to load the lubridate package

Code 
library(lubridate)

Then, youâll want to convert the start of Taylorâs concert to a date-time object called concert_start. Youâll also want to convert the time the Super Bowl starts into a date-time object called super_bowl_start. Remember to set the approprate tzs for each respective time zone.

Code 
# Convert the start of Taylor's concert to a date-time object called `concert_start`. Remember to set the approprate `tz`
concert_start <- ymd_hm("2024-02-10 18:00", tz = "Asia/Tokyo")

# Convert the time the Super Bowl starts into a date-time object called `super_bowl_start`. Remember to set the approprate `tz`
super_bowl_start <- ymd_hm("2024-02-11 15:30", tz = "America/Los_Angeles")

3 Simple time math

Now that your times are all created, letâs figure out when Taylorâs concert ends, and call that concert_end

Code 
# Calculate when Taylor's concert ends, and call that `concert_end`
concert_end <- concert_start + hours(5)

Of course, we all know that airports take tons of time to meander through. However, since Taylor is something of a demi-goddess, she has access to a private jet. And because she loves her boyfriend so much, sheâs willing to bite the carbon bullet and fly herself to Las Vegas. So, letâs add an additional hour to Taylorâs concert_end time and call that take_off. Then, add the time it will take to fly all the way to Las Vegas and call that vegas_land.

Code 
#Calculate Taylor's take-off time
take_off <- concert_end + hours(1)

#Calculate when Taylor will land in Las Vegas after a 13-hour flight
vegas_land <- take_off + hours(13)

4 Get her to the Allegiant

Taylor has landed in Las Vegas! Fortunately, the stadium is only a few miles away, but Taylor isnât interested in taking chances. She has decided to take a private helicopter to the stadium, which will be ready for her when she lands. Add another 15 minutes to her vegas_land time to create her time of being dropped off at Allegiant Stadium, and call this drop_off

Code 
#Calculate when Taylor will arrive above Allegiant Stadium, ready to parachute down
drop_off <- vegas_land + minutes(15)

But wait! Taylor has always wanted to sky dive! And what a great entrance that would be (eat your heart out, Usher). Taylor has decided that she will take the parachute from the helicopter and drop down onto the field. Since it only take about 5 minutes to reach the ground after jumping, letâs call this touch_down (pun may or may not have been intended, but was fully appreciated).

Code 
#Calculate how long it takes Taylor to float down to the ground
touch_down <- drop_off + minutes(5)

5 Jet lag, anybody?

Taylor has landed in Vegas, she has climbed aboard a private helicopter, and she has had the experience of a lifetime falling from the sky into Allegiant Stadium. But she is a bit disoriented after all of this rushing and plummeting, and her analogue wrist watch (yes sheâs that oldskool) is still set to Tokyo time! She needs to figure out what time it is in Vegas. Letâs convert her touch_down time to PST and call it touch_down_PST.

Code 
#Convert `touch_down` date-time object to PST time
touch_down_PST <- with_tz(touch_down, tzone = "America/Los_Angeles")

Taylor needed to be there by 3:30pm on February 11th, 2024. All Taylor needs to know if she made it there before then to give her boyfriend a good luck smooch. Letâs create a way to determine if she made it on time so that it gives us a Boolean data type.

Code 
#Determine if Taylor's touch down time is before the start of the Super Bowl
was_she_swift_enough <- touch_down_PST < super_bowl_start

was_she_swift_enough
[1] TRUE

6 She must do whatâs right.

She made it! But Taylor feels bad about the carbon footprint she has left taking the private jet. Now that she is in Vegas, she believes that it is her moral duty to go gambling, to wield her newly discovered card-counting technique she learned on her 13-hour flight, and to make enough money so that she can offset the jet fuel emissions by donating it to the Rainforest Alliance. Letâs see how much time Taylor has to work with by finding the difference between her touch_down_PST time and the super_bowl_start time.

Code 
#If she was, how much time did she have to spare?
time_difference <- difftime(super_bowl_start, touch_down_PST, units = "hours")

time_difference
Time difference of 19.16667 hours

7 How much does she have to make per hour?

After some complex math with Taylorâs private environmental consultant, she has determined that she needs to make at least $3,000 to offset her carbon footprint from her flight. With the amount of time she has left, letâs figure out how much money per hour she has to win from her gambling adventures in order to pay off the $3,000 before the Super Bowl starts. Remember to convert the time_difference object to a numeric object that you can use!

Code 
hours_left = as.numeric(time_difference, units = "hours")

money_per_hour = 3000 / hours_left

## The Prompt

Use lubridate to make an argument about whether Taylor can make it from her concert in Tokyo, Japan, on Saturday, 2/10/2024, at 6:00pm (you can assume the concert lasts about 5 hours) to the Super Bowl in Las Vegas, Nevada, on Sunday, 2/11/2024, at 3:30pm.

```{r}
knitr::include_graphics("swift_FP.png")
```


## Getting set up
First, you'll want to load the `lubridate` package

```{r}
library(lubridate)
```

Then, you'll want to convert the start of Taylor's concert to a date-time object called `concert_start`. You'll also want to convert the time the Super Bowl starts into a date-time object called `super_bowl_start`. Remember to set the approprate `tz`s for each respective time zone.

```{r}
# Convert the start of Taylor's concert to a date-time object called `concert_start`. Remember to set the approprate `tz`
concert_start <- ymd_hm("2024-02-10 18:00", tz = "Asia/Tokyo")

# Convert the time the Super Bowl starts into a date-time object called `super_bowl_start`. Remember to set the approprate `tz`
super_bowl_start <- ymd_hm("2024-02-11 15:30", tz = "America/Los_Angeles")
```

## Simple time math

Now that your times are all created, let's figure out when Taylor's concert ends, and call that `concert_end`
```{r}
# Calculate when Taylor's concert ends, and call that `concert_end`
concert_end <- concert_start + hours(5)
```


Of course, we all know that airports take tons of time to meander through. However, since Taylor is something of a demi-goddess, she has access to a private jet. And because she loves her boyfriend so much, she's willing to bite the carbon bullet and fly herself to Las Vegas. So, let's add an additional hour to Taylor's `concert_end` time and call that `take_off`. Then, add the time it will take to fly all the way to Las Vegas and call that `vegas_land`.
```{r}
#Calculate Taylor's take-off time
take_off <- concert_end + hours(1)

#Calculate when Taylor will land in Las Vegas after a 13-hour flight
vegas_land <- take_off + hours(13)
```

## Get her to the Allegiant

Taylor has landed in Las Vegas! Fortunately, the stadium is only a few miles away, but Taylor isn't interested in taking chances. She has decided to take a private helicopter to the stadium, which will be ready for her when she lands. Add another 15 minutes to her `vegas_land` time to create her time of being dropped off at Allegiant Stadium, and call this `drop_off`
```{r}
#Calculate when Taylor will arrive above Allegiant Stadium, ready to parachute down
drop_off <- vegas_land + minutes(15)
```

But wait! Taylor has always wanted to sky dive! And what a great entrance that would be (eat your heart out, Usher). Taylor has decided that she will take the parachute from the helicopter and drop down onto the field. Since it only take about `5` minutes to reach the ground after jumping, let's call this `touch_down` (pun may or may not have been intended, but was fully appreciated).
```{r}
#Calculate how long it takes Taylor to float down to the ground
touch_down <- drop_off + minutes(5)
```

## Jet lag, anybody?

Taylor has landed in Vegas, she has climbed aboard a private helicopter, and she has had the experience of a lifetime falling from the sky into Allegiant Stadium. But she is a bit disoriented after all of this rushing and plummeting, and her analogue wrist watch (yes she's that oldskool) is still set to Tokyo time! She needs to figure out what time it is in Vegas. Let's convert her `touch_down` time to PST and call it `touch_down_PST`.
```{r}
#Convert `touch_down` date-time object to PST time
touch_down_PST <- with_tz(touch_down, tzone = "America/Los_Angeles")
```


Taylor needed to be there by 3:30pm on February 11th, 2024. All Taylor needs to know if she made it there before then to give her boyfriend a good luck smooch. Let's create a way to determine if she made it on time so that it gives us a Boolean data type.
```{r}
#Determine if Taylor's touch down time is before the start of the Super Bowl
was_she_swift_enough <- touch_down_PST < super_bowl_start

was_she_swift_enough
```

## She must do what's right.

She made it! But Taylor feels bad about the carbon footprint she has left taking the private jet. Now that she is in Vegas, she believes that it is her moral duty to go gambling, to wield her newly discovered card-counting technique she learned on her 13-hour flight, and to make enough money so that she can offset the jet fuel emissions by donating it to the Rainforest Alliance. Let's see how much time Taylor has to work with by finding the difference between her `touch_down_PST` time and the `super_bowl_start` time.
```{r}
#If she was, how much time did she have to spare?
time_difference <- difftime(super_bowl_start, touch_down_PST, units = "hours")

time_difference

```

## How much does she have to make per hour?

After some complex math with Taylor's private environmental consultant, she has determined that she needs to make at least **$3,000** to offset her carbon footprint from her flight. With the amount of time she has left, let's figure out how much money per hour she has to win from her gambling adventures in order to pay off the $3,000 before the Super Bowl starts. Remember to convert the `time_difference` object to a numeric object that you can use!
```{r}
hours_left = as.numeric(time_difference, units = "hours")

money_per_hour = 3000 / hours_left

money_per_hour

```

Well there we have it! We know that she'll make it with plenty of time to hustle the casinos and make the world a greener place for her trouble. She just has to make **~$156/hour**, which I'm sure she can manage. 

I look forward to seeing how her presence influences the game! Maybe it will be just what the Chiefs need to barely eke out a victory with three seconds left in overtime, but that's just a wild guess.
